segments.text: In those early years, what courses did you teach?
I taught agricultural prices, agricultural policy, and futures and options markets.
These were three-hour courses.
Three-hour courses, and then I taught a futures and options course at both the graduate, well, not the early years, no, just those three.
They were undergraduate?
Yeah.
Juniors and seniors?
Well, one of them, I'm sorry, one of them was a graduate.
Well, okay, I taught undergraduate prices and graduate prices.
Price analysis is a big deal in agricultural economics.
Then I taught ag policy at the graduate level, and then I taught futures and options at the undergraduate level.
And normally these were, the students who took those were majoring in what?
They did major in agricultural economics.
These were almost all majors.
These weren't service courses.
All right, and by the time we get to the late 60s, there are women admitted
How long was it before you had some coeds in those classes?
Well, a while.
We didn't have, you didn't have any females in agricultural economics.
I'm trying to think.
There were few and far between until just recent years, by recent I mean the last 10, 15.
I can't really
If you remember, I guess we had some in the early 70s, but there weren't many.
Of those early courses, which one was your favorite?
Which one did you enjoy most?
Well, I think probably the most fun was the Futures and Options course because it was something that was happening daily.
You could check the newspaper.
The markets went up and down.
It was very applied.
Give some examples of some of the changes, sharp changes or lack thereof that you could relate to in class.
Well, every day was a new day in the futures market because whatever happened overnight would affect whether it was weather or international policy changes or war or whatever.
You'd have a new set of prices the next day in the futures market, which you could use as examples.
And then when you had
drought situations like you have now, or when you have surplus situations.
Of course, you had dramatic changes in prices.
And there was always a daily example to use in your teaching.
And out of the Wall Street Journal, you could cut almost every day in the Commodities column, there was something you could talk about which was going on in the real world.
So unlike history, where I had to revise my notes every year, which I'm sure is going to do, too.
Did they have term papers?
I had a term paper.
We had an ongoing futures trading problem, which they would turn in their trades like once a week for as many as, I don't know, two or three commodities they kept track of.
And then at the end, they had to write this up as a series of hedges or risk management exercises in the futures course.
Then in the price analysis course, they were supposed to try
to explain the price behavior for some commodity, which is pretty tough for anybody.
Most of us aren't very good at that.
But that was the assignment.
Yeah, term papers are more prevalent then than they are now, I think.
In terms of the student body, students in those courses, what commodities were of least interest and of most interest to them?
Well, cotton and wheat are big in Texas.
See, that's part of what's changed, too, is when I got here, almost everybody on the faculty was a farm boy.
Mm-hmm.
They had come from farming or farm-related.
And the students, I think, were almost 100% probably agriculture or agriculture community.
And over the times, that has changed greatly.
I suppose they were probably going back to agriculture.
Not now.
Not at all, not now.
The major commodities of interest to them were the ones in Texas where they'd come from.
Cotton, wheat, cattle.
If it was in the valley, it could have been
orange juice because it was a frozen concentrated orange juice futures contract.
So it's mainly because of where they're from.
For you as a mature adult, were you ever struck by the fact that they should have been more interested in this commodity or that one, but apparently were not?
Well, not so much.
Once in a while, they get enamored with gold futures because they thought, well, here's the chance to make big bucks.
I'll become a speculator.
And you had to talk them out of that and tell them, no, we're interested in just the opposite.
We're trying to manage risk, not create it.
But you'd get kids that would go off the deep end once in a while in some commodity like gold or silver, platinum, futures.
By and large, what would have been the typical enrollment in a section in those years?
40 would have been big.
25 to 35 students.
That was what our big classroom
was probably 50, our big classroom, and that was not always full.
Now, did you have a TA or any kind of an assistant?
Yeah, we always had TAs, as I recall.
We had good teaching support from a teaching assistant standpoint, and if you wanted to, depending on the schedule, you wanted to use them.
And I usually graded my own tests, but they would grade the exercises, things like that.
Yeah, we had good support.
Share some anecdotes of faculty-student relations in those 60s and 70s, those earlier years, when it was largely an all-male student body.
Yeah, again, the students, I don't know if it was sort of the Aggie Corps thing, but they were not hostile, but they were, at least I felt a little bit, we do our thing and you do yours.
You know, when we come to class, we do, we may be sleeping in class, but we come to class.
They did come to class, they didn't cut class,
And they did their work.
I didn't run, I was not advisor, strangely enough, I was never advisor to a core unit.

So I didn't get into, we had kids over to our house, like I can remember we had a core commander over there and when we were with the MSC council with Wayne Stark, we got to know a lot of student leadership through SCONA and things like that, where we had good student interaction with the students.
But I don't remember any other than helping a bunch of students get down off of the Ag building the week before Christmas where they had been perhaps drinking something they shouldn't have been.
And they were up there singing.
And somebody in the library complained.
And when the police came, I helped talk them out of taking them to jail.
Other than that, I can't remember any really glaring.
student relations problems.

What about students trying, giving you some kind of excuse that you thought might have been stretching the truth about... You had a few that you weren't ever too sure about people, how sick they were and so on.
Mostly thinking about their work.
There wasn't a lot of that.
Most people kind of like, they minded their business, it seemed to me like it, were pretty straight up with it.
So I don't have any creative
Nothing about turning in a paper late or why they missed the final?
No, didn't have a lot of that trouble.
It's amazing how many people got married at the end of the semester that seemed to have to be out in somebody's wedding.
That turned up a lot, which we had to try to work around on occasion.
One of the most interesting things I ran into was, this was in later years, I found a student who had hired a tutor who was sitting in on the course with him.
I had never encountered that before, and the guy had presented it to me, the tutor had presented it to me, and said, you know, I'm just really interested in our course economics.
Would it be okay if I just sat in on this course?
Sure, I'm not going to discourage intellectual, you know, motivation.

So he did, and it came to find out that he was doing the same thing in another course, and the two of us got together, the two professors, accidentally, two teachers, and found out this guy was actually hiring this guy as a tutor.
So I put a stop to that.
Did you find out what the fee was?
No, I didn't.
I just said, man, you're out of here.
That would have been when?
In the 90s?
Yes, it was in the 90s.
I'd never heard of it before.
Maybe it went on, but no, I didn't.
Because you didn't have that many people visiting your class.
And what about scholastic dishonesty in those early years?
Well, fortunately, or frequently, your classroom would be such that you could place people...
a desk between them.
And if not, you tried to use A and B tests, you know, and things like that.
But I don't.
Now, Curtis Lord tells me that, you know, cheating is rampant now.
I don't know that it is.
I don't remember having that much trouble with it.
Once in a while you'd catch somebody who had the A answers on the B test, and that was a clear-cut case, and you'd tell them, you know, you're out of here or something.
Nobody ever contested it.
Nowadays, I'm not sure what you might, probably might get into if you had to go to court or something like that.
But I didn't notice a lot of them.
Maybe I was just naive.

Did anybody in your almost 40 years, did anybody in a position of authority ever infer to you or candidly tell you that you needed to pass a certain percentage or flunk a certain percentage or anything like that?
Nobody ever told me how to teach a course.
Nobody ever told me
Well, I did get a call from the athletic department once about a kid who subsequently was out of here anyhow, inquiring about some grade and if I was sure I had it right and so on and so forth.
I wasn't sure what the message was, but they never did pursue it.
But nobody ever called me in the dean's office and said, you know, we need to have a different grade here.
At least I don't recall ever being interfered with in a classroom.
As far as I was concerned, I had total academic freedom at that level, which was either good or bad news because maybe I needed more direction than I got.
But nobody ever interfered that way.
And in those early years, where did you post your grades?
On the wall with the name and the number.
Everybody saw everybody's grades.
Had you encountered that at Penn State or Oklahoma A&M?
I can't recall that we didn't.
I mean, I'm not saying I don't remember.
We probably did, but... We didn't do that at Rice or Austin College, no.
See, I'm not recalling that we posted the grades that way, but we sure did here, that's right.
In the department in those early years, were there some key courses that, according to the students, were the tough courses?
Yeah, we introduced one sort of an econometrics-type course at the undergraduate level.
That was sort of a filter course.
Then I think they probably thought Production Economics 325 was a lot of work.
I'm not sure about 105.
That was our introductory course.
Who taught it?
Everybody took that.
J.C. Grady.
J.C. Grady taught the 105.
He was the father, so to speak, of the undergraduate section.
But I would guess those are the ones, the 317,
econometrics course.
Now, that was in agricultural economics.
I think when you went over to economics, see we took courses all over the place, in business and economics, some of the tech fields, animal science and so on.
Probably the toughest time to have would be over in economics, having maybe income and employment or
and that sort of thing, macroeconomics.
Were there any courses in the department that supposedly, according to the students, were kind of easy, kind of crip courses?
Well, I'm sure there were, and we had a guy named Dr. Dan, the grade point man, but that was sociology.
Yeah, what did you hear from the students about, where did he get that nickname and why?
Well, I presume that he was fairly easy on the grading.
I don't know, but he...
Dr. Dan had gotten his, he had a cut on his nose.
It clearly had been cut.
The legend was that he'd gotten a knife fight or somebody had knifed him.
His degree was from the University of Chicago.
I believe he had a master's.
He may have been a PhD.
I'm not sure.
But other than that course, again, I didn't have that much.
Some guys have a much better or closer or whatever, I guess, relationship with students.
Not that I didn't talk to the students.
Not that my door wasn't open.
But I didn't have a lot of interaction with students.
Let's see, this is Dan Davis.
No, no, this wasn't Dan Davis.
Dan Russell.
Dan Russell.
Yeah, Dan Russell.
And he's the one that deserves credit for thinking up the project house idea back in the Depression.
I didn't do that.
I believe he's the one.
Dr. Dan.
He was a fine old gentleman.
Of course, all these guys were.
Because I heard a legend once.
I heard a legend one time that he had posted his grades and there was an appropriate A, B, C, D, E, F break.
And a student came to the department wanting to check on his grades and the secretary looked in the grade book and he had gotten a higher grade turned in than the grade posted on the door.
What?
He really didn't.
Now that's just a myth, I don't know.
Let's go back to your point on grading because when I got here, grades were 93 and up was an A.
There were 70 and below was an F. Yes.
And only 30 points were for actual, the D was 70 through 77, I think, or 76.
So it was grading, when it reduced to 60, I don't know if that was the Vietnam War or when they brought that in, but
That changed, that certainly changed the grading system.
But when you as a new faculty member gave a grade on an essay test, didn't you first decide whether this question deserved an A, B, C, D, or F?
And then you assigned the appropriate points under that system.
Well, each question had its own points, its own weight.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, right.
Well, no, actually, when I got through, I just looked at total points.
No, but was it tougher to make an A under that system?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
You think it was?
Oh, yeah.
Well, you mean under the system now?
Yeah, because we had just squished it up.
So there was a, yeah, I think grading was tougher back then.
I mean, I think it was lower.
All right, as the years go, as we're going to start going now chronologically,
You think that the typical member of the department, and particularly you, thought it was good for A&M to make the changes in co-education, non-compulsory core, racial integration, and so forth?
Yes, I think that was agreed.
Do you remember any departmental realities regarding the first female students, how they were received and so forth?
You know, that's a good question.
I really don't.
There would have been so few that they would have been noticed, that's for sure.
But you don't remember any?
I don't remember any adverse or positive.
What about black students?
Aspects of that.
Gosh, black students came so late to our department.
We get so few black students in agricultural economics.
Fred McClure sticks out.
I was about to say.
Yeah, yeah.
But they're rare as undergraduates, even as graduate students.
We don't get many black students.
Describe what you recall about Fred McClure as a student and as a leader.
Strangely enough, Fred is one guy I missed in my course.
In my course, everybody had to pass through it.
But that year, somebody else taught it.
We taught two sections, and I didn't get to have Fred in the class.
But he was a presence to be reckoned with and very active.
very popular, but I never did really get to know him through a class.
I missed him, and I regret that because he, and I've known him better later when he comes back to the department, but he was certainly exceptional, no question about that.
When did you all begin to get any international undergraduate students?
Well, first of all, we don't have many international undergraduate students.
Graduate students, yes.
Mexico, I think probably we'd get some few from Mexico.
But it'd be interesting to know today just how many we have international, very few international graduate students.
Not a whole lot out of state undergraduates.
We're so heavily Texan.
And geographically, where down through the years, where have the undergraduate students come from in Texas?
Well, through the years, it's changed.
I mean, you know, now it's Houston, what, Houston, Dallas, San Antonio, Austin.
Then it was like towns.
But still, even in agricultural economics, I noticed up until recent years, I had kids fill out every first of my class, I always had them fill out a slip.
Where are you from?
Hometown.
What was your hometown mascot?
You know, your high school mascot, stuff like that.
And I was surprised how many of them came from small towns, even in the 90s.
The ones we were getting here were, many were from small towns.
There were some from Houston and places, but still a lot of rural areas in Texas are sending them at least into agricultural economics.
And as far as you were aware, they thought that they were going into the real world of agricultural economics.
Well, they did, and yet if you'd ask them how many are going back to the farm, they weren't.
There were very few who were going back to the farm.
You know, two or three hands might go up in the whole class.
But agribusiness has become the word of the day.
We have changed, and that's part of the name change controversy.
What do we change our name to?
And many agricultural economics departments have changed their name to agriculture and applied economics or something like that, or agribusiness economics.
And we haven't, but we have an agribusiness major, and it's very popular.
It's with the business school, so you have to have a little higher grades to get into it.
But so they go, most of them do go to work with something agriculture-related, but a significant number don't.
I mean, they go out totally divorced from agriculture.
All right, in the early years when you get here, about,
What was the proportion of the graduate enrollment to the undergraduate in majors?
Well, it'd be much, much less.
When I was, we had, first of all, we didn't have a Ph.D. program, as I recall.
Okay.
I don't think we had a Ph.D. program.
So we had master's.
I could be wrong on that, but I don't.
I reckon how many master's degrees be finished a year?
Yeah, well, I don't know, four, five, six, maybe.
So it was much more heavily undergraduate.
When I was sort of administering the graduate program, we had 200 graduate students.
When was that?
That would have been, oh, late 70s and through the 80s.
I had that about 9 or 10 years.
Gave it up in 87 or something like that, 88, I don't know.
And we had 200 graduate students, 40 or 50 of those
were really Ivan Shmederman's real estate students.
But they were part of our department.
And 50 PhDs, 100 master of science.
Oh, man, I'm not used to talking this much.
And then we had at one time, we peaked out, I think, at 800 undergraduates.
So we were close to 1,000 in this department.
We're not that high now.
And we're not that many graduate students now.
Those graduate students, where were they from geographically?
Most of them would have been from Texas.
A few you get from the north, northeast.
What about international?
International, mostly Asian, and some from Africa, a few from Africa.
We got, at a certain point in time, we got a lot of Peace Corps kids come back through here, female Peace Corps kids.
I can count five, six, seven.
who are now out in professional positions as agricultural economists who were Peace Corps females.
And then also males came back.
We got a slug of Peace Corps people, still get some Peace Corps people.

I think they come back, you know, seeing that eating is important and they want to feed the world and they typically get a degree and go into a regular professional agri-economics position somewhere in a faculty.
But we've never been heavy on, we've gotten a few from, I can name like one or two guys from the Netherlands
We had one through here from Germany, but not many from Western Europe have we had in graduate school.
Now, Dr. Tim served as department head until about when?
Well, I want to say around 1970.
I want to say.
That may be too late, but I think so, yeah.
When did the department have any discussions about how it was going to progress to become bigger, better, stronger?
Oh, yeah.
We had departmental studies.

couldn't pull them off the shelf for you, but I don't know if it was mandated from the top down or we thought it up ourselves, but where are we going, whom should we be serving, who's our audience, what's our mission, how do we want to, you know, and continual sort of a rolling thing on are we teaching the right courses and stuff like that.
So we've had, there's a name for those studies, but I can't think of it right now.
As you recall those discussions,
What did the department normally agree upon as the strengths and the weaknesses of the department at that?
Well, we had to sort of pick among areas.
Like in agricultural economics, you have marketing, production economics, resource economics, community economics, and so on.
And we sort of decided, well, we're going to try to get good in marketing.
We're going to be good in marketing.

and little left synthesis maybe on production economics or something and do less of that more of the more resource economics that got popular not going to do labor economics you know stuff but i can't i think probably marketing dr tim's sort of favorite marketing and policy he liked agricultural policy so we have an agricultural policy center here which i'm not sure how instrumental he was in it but that we do have one
Did the dean and vice president of academic affairs, was there support for this effort above the departmental level, as far as you all know?
You mean studying?
Well, this progress that you all were hoping to make.
Haskell, I don't know.
I couldn't tell you.
But you don't know of anything where you all sent forth a recommendation, it was turned down?
No, I don't know that there wasn't support for it.
I just don't know.
what happened at those levels.
Did you all feel like that there was some fiscal ability to make some of these changes?
Yeah, I think so.
And, again, back in those days where you got your money allocated by formula from the federal sources, and state support was, I think, probably not too bad in Texas.
I'm not sure how it stacked up compared to Iowa or something like that.
But I don't think resources were all that limiting at that time.

uh... and i think we looked at other departments i think ty did and then john hopkin came in from illinois who was new blood as department head and he'd been around he'd been vice president of bank of america or something in california or that bank of america i'm not sure where his office was but uh... he was new blood new directions and his idea was just to hire as many good people as he can and he did but i think ty looked at other departments to see what they were doing describe uh... hopkin
He came about in 1970?
Yeah, he would have come from Illinois.
He had been, I believe, vice president of Bank of America in San Francisco, California.
John was a finance.
Agricultural finance became a really hot issue and a hot item, and we started hiring finance people right after John got here, some of them from the University of Illinois.
But John's approach was, I'm going to hire the best people I can and then let them do what they want to do.

and, you know, let them get their own money, or give them money as I can, but he was, he wasn't an automatic pilot, but he was pretty much a more academic, he was a more academic department head, I think, and probably Ty was a little more authoritarian.
In the search for a new department head, was there any departmental involvement?
Yeah, there certainly was, there must have been with John,
I know there was quite a bit with Padberg when he came in.
But with Hopkins, I'm sure there was some, yes.
I just can't remember how extensive it was.
I'm sure he came for an interview.
And in his personal religious faith, he was a newcomer, wasn't he?
Yeah, yeah.
There weren't many LDS, and John certainly was that.
He was prominent, I know, in the church.
Describe his leadership style.
Well, I think John was an enabler.
He would help you.
If you'd go and explain to him why you thought you wanted to do something and you justified, he would try to help you.
As I say, his policy, I think, basically, as I observed it, was I'm going to hire the best people I can and then let them do their thing.
He wasn't heavy-handed, and I think he took pretty good care of us.
He had some fights with the...
fights, I say, with the dean or with the director of the experiment station in a good-natured fashion.
I think they were pretty much good-natured, but I think he would go to bat for the department and try to get some things that he thought were needed.
Did you all feel that he had the same level of influence, comparatively speaking, that Dr. Tim did?
Well, he didn't have the old boy hookups.
He wasn't an Aggie.
He wasn't a Texan.
But I think that he...
and was pretty able to hold his own, yeah.
And Dr. Tim ceased being department head because of retirement.
Yeah, and Ty, yes, I think it was that, partly his health, but I think retirement.
At that time, didn't you have to retire at a certain age?
Yeah.
I think that's what got him.
And Ty, he didn't live very long after that.
Well, and what I wanted to make clear is that it was not, he wasn't a terminator.
No, no, no, I never had.
knowledge that he was forced out or anything.
I don't think so.
And by this time, Harry Kunkel is the dean.
Right.
And did the department have any impression of him, you think?
Well, I think he was a very good researcher and teacher.
Dr. Kunkel was clearly an intellectual, I think.
He was a thinker.
And impression as a dean, I'm not sure he
He was dean and director, let's see, of Experiment Station?
Both, maybe?
Yeah.
Terrible, I can't remember.
But he'll tell you.
President Rutter dies in early 1970.
What did you and your colleagues, what was your perception of him as Texas A&M's president and leader?
Well, he was clearly not really tuned to the academic scene, we thought, of course, as young Turks, but very respected, I think, for his honesty and forthrightness.

I always thought of him as like Nixon going to China, that only Nixon could go to China because of who he was, and only President Rudder could have integrated Texas A&M both racially and even more so female thing.
He was the man for the time.
Certainly Morgan couldn't have done it before him, I don't think.
He just did that.
And I think he was fair-minded.
Probably would have liked to have been approached more by the faculty than he was.
And I think probably he may have felt somewhat isolated from the faculty because he wasn't, you know, a degreed, in a sense, terminal degreed person.
But I don't think he was, I think he was certainly respected, and I think he was a man for the time and the place, just ideal.
Did you all ever talk about his ability as a public speaker?
Yeah, yeah, bless his heart.
You know, he just really didn't turn you on that way.
I mean, you were patient, but he, and I think he knew it.
I think he knew he was not a public speaker, but I think he dreaded it.
I don't think he looked forward to it at all.
Were you aware that his health was declining not long before his death?
Well, it's amazing how, you know, you see people change when they get in the office.
And when he came in, he was a fairly... looked like a normal person.
But I noticed that he just ballooned over time and just...
He really looked like the...
I think the strain on him must have been fantastic.
It must have been.
And, of course, you eat all those rubber chicken and pea dinners, and he just didn't handle that well.
I mean, I think he was...
Maybe he was just too conscientious.
He just bore too much stress.
He didn't take care of himself.
